      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/sqa-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023R2) is a commercially licensed, FDA-recognized simulation software with documented software quality assurance procedures. Vendor-supplied verification test suite passes all benchmark cases. Internal SQA checklist (revision-controlled, signed off by lead analyst and independent reviewer) confirms version control, input-file traceability, and output archiving. All simulation runs executed on configuration-managed HPC cluster with checksummed executables. SQA level exceeds MRL 2 requirement; no open SQA findings.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/sqa"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/code-verification-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed using the Method of Manufactured Solutions (MMS) for the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations and the power-law hemolysis transport equation. Observed order of accuracy matches theoretical second-order accuracy of the spatial discretization scheme (p_obs = 1.97 ± 0.04). Code verification suite includes 8 canonical benchmark cases (lid-driven cavity, backward-facing step, rotating disk, Poiseuille flow) all passing to within solver tolerance. Results archived in revision-controlled repository with traceability to solver version.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/code-verification"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/discretization-error-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Discretization error was rigorously quantified using the Grid Convergence Index (GCI) methodology per Roache (1994) and ASME V&V 20. Three systematically refined hexahedral meshes were constructed with refinement ratio r = 2 (1.2M, 4.8M, 19.2M cells). Richardson extrapolation applied to both NIH and delta-P quantities of interest. GCI_fine = 1.4% for NIH and 0.9% for delta-P, both well within the 5% acceptance threshold. Asymptotic convergence confirmed (GCI ratio = 1.02). Discretization error contribution bounded and incorporated into total uncertainty budget. Temporal discretization verified via time-step refinement study showing < 0.5% variation in cycle-averaged NIH.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/discretization-error"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-conditions-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions used for validation are documented in the FDA flow-loop experimental protocol. Five operating points span the clinical CPB envelope (flow rates 2–6 L/min, rotational speeds 1500–3500 RPM). Blood analog fluid (glycerol-saline with bovine red blood cells, hematocrit 35 ± 1%) prepared and characterized per ASTM F1841. Temperature controlled at 37 ± 0.5°C throughout. Inlet turbulence intensity measured via LDV and applied as boundary condition. All test conditions traceable to calibrated instrumentation with NIST-traceable calibration certificates. Boundary condition uncertainty quantified and propagated through CFD model.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-conditions"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/output-comparison-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed between CFD predictions and experimental measurements using multiple metrics: (1) mean absolute relative error (MARE = 8.3% for NIH across 5 operating points), (2) Pearson correlation coefficient (r = 0.97), (3) U95 validation uncertainty metric per ASME V&V 20 confirming model is within validation uncertainty at all operating points. Bland-Altman analysis shows no systematic bias. Comparison extended to secondary QoIs (pressure rise, wall shear stress distribution) with consistent agreement. All comparison plots archived with traceability to raw experimental data and CFD output files.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/output-comparison"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest (NIH — normalized index of hemolysis) is directly mapped to the clinical hemolysis endpoint via the relative hemolysis index (RH) acceptance criterion (RH < 1 vs. predicate device). NIH is the FDA-recognized metric for computational hemolysis assessment per FDA guidance on blood-contacting devices. Secondary QoIs (pump pressure rise, wall shear stress, exposure time distributions) are mechanistically linked to the hemolysis model and validated independently. QoI selection documented in the modeling and simulation plan with explicit traceability from device safety claim to model output. No surrogate or indirect QoIs used without documented justification.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/qoi-relevance"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were designed to span the COU operating envelope. The FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry used in validation is the same geometry used in the COU predictions, eliminating geometric extrapolation uncertainty. Operating conditions in validation experiments (flow rates, RPM, fluid properties) bracket the 5 worst-case operating points identified in the COU. Validation domain overlap score (per FDA 2021 guidance framework) assessed as HIGH for geometry, MEDIUM-HIGH for operating conditions, and HIGH for fluid properties. Any extrapolation from validation domain to COU is bounded and documented with supporting sensitivity analysis.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/validation-relevance"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/solver-error-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error was assessed through iterative convergence monitoring and residual analysis. All simulations converged to normalized residuals below 1e-6 for continuity, momentum, and hemolysis transport equations. Mass conservation error < 0.01% across all simulations. Double-precision arithmetic used throughout to minimize round-off error. Solver settings (relaxation factors, discretization schemes) documented and fixed across all production runs. Iterative convergence contribution to total uncertainty budget estimated at < 0.1% via sensitivity study on convergence tolerance. No solver divergence or non-physical oscillations observed in any of the 500 UQ ensemble runs.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/solver-error"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/use-error-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Use error controls implemented at multiple levels: (1) simulation setup checklist reviewed and signed by independent analyst prior to each production run; (2) automated input-file validation script checks boundary condition consistency, mesh quality metrics (max skewness < 0.85, min orthogonality > 0.15), and material property assignments; (3) post-processing scripts version-controlled with unit tests; (4) independent analyst reproduced 2 of 5 operating-point simulations from raw inputs, confirming identical results within floating-point precision; (5) all analyst training records and competency assessments on file. No use errors identified during independent reproduction exercise.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-form-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty assessed through systematic comparison of three hemolysis model formulations: (1) Giersiepen power-law model, (2) Zhang modified power-law model, and (3) Taskin Lagrangian particle-tracking model. The Zhang model was selected as primary based on superior agreement with experimental NIH data (MARE = 8.3% vs. 14.7% for Giersiepen). Model form uncertainty contribution estimated as the inter-model spread (±12% of NIH at worst-case operating point) and incorporated into total uncertainty budget. Turbulence model sensitivity study compared k-ω SST, k-ε realizable, and RSM; k-ω SST selected with < 3% sensitivity on NIH. All model form choices documented with justification in modeling and simulation plan.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-inputs-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "All model inputs characterized with documented uncertainty distributions. Blood viscosity modeled as non-Newtonian (Carreau model) with parameters fit to rheometry data (n=6 donors, 95% CI reported). Inlet velocity profiles derived from LDV measurements with spatial uncertainty quantified. Pump geometry digitized from CMM measurements (±5 µm tolerance). Hemolysis model coefficients (C, α, β) assigned literature-derived distributions with covariance structure. Global sensitivity analysis (Sobol indices, n=500 Monte Carlo ensemble) identifies rotational speed and flow rate as dominant inputs; geometric tolerances contribute < 5% to NIH variance. All input uncertainty distributions traceable to primary measurement data or peer-reviewed literature sources.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-samples-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Test samples used in validation experiments are representative of the COU device population. Three pump units fabricated from the same production tooling as the COU device were tested. Unit-to-unit geometric variability characterized via CMM (max dimensional deviation 18 µm, within 5% of nominal clearances). Blood analog prepared from bovine red blood cells with hematocrit 35 ± 1% and viability confirmed via osmotic fragility test prior to each experiment. Sample size of 3 units provides adequate coverage of manufacturing variability at MRL 2. Between-unit variability in NIH measurements (CV = 4.2%) incorporated into experimental uncertainty budget.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/input-equivalency-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Equivalency between validation experiment input parameters and COU simulation input parameters formally assessed using a parameter equivalency matrix. All 12 primary input parameters (geometry, fluid properties, operating conditions, boundary conditions) compared between validation and COU contexts. Seven parameters are identical (same geometry, same fluid model, same rotational speed range). Three parameters have documented minor differences (inlet turbulence intensity ±2%, temperature ±1°C, hematocrit ±2%) with sensitivity analysis confirming < 3% impact on NIH for each. Two parameters (outlet pressure specification, wall roughness) are within validated range. No parameter extrapolation outside validated domain without bounding uncertainty analysis. Equivalency assessment documented and reviewed by independent analyst.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/input-equivalency"
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/actor/credibility-assessment-team-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CFD hemolysis prediction for CPB Class II device, MRL 2) is accepted based on the following structured evidence review: All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed and all achieve levels at or above the required level for MRL 2. Verification activities (SQA, code verification, discretization error, solver error) confirm the numerical model is correctly implemented and solved with quantified numerical uncertainty (total numerical uncertainty < 3% of NIH). Validation activities demonstrate agreement between CFD predictions and FDA flow-loop experimental data within validation uncertainty bounds at all 5 operating points (MARE = 8.3%, r = 0.97), with validation domain relevance confirmed as HIGH for geometry and fluid properties. Uncertainty quantification via Monte Carlo ensemble (n=500) confirms that the 95% confidence interval on RH remains below 1.0 across the COU operating envelope, satisfying the acceptance criterion. Model form uncertainty assessed through multi-model comparison and bounded at ±12% of NIH. Use error controls including independent reproduction and automated input validation provide high confidence in correct model application. The combined evidence chain — from foundational experimental data through verified solver, validated hemolysis model, and propagated uncertainty budget — supports the claim that the CFD model can reliably identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the Class II CPB device. Decision consequence is HIGH and model influence is MEDIUM; the structured evidence at MRL 2 is commensurate with this risk level. No weakeners identified. Package accepted for regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
